      The algorithm works on its own to find patterns and information and it makes a prediction based on what it has learned.
    </p>

    <p data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1500" data-aos-delay="150">
      One way of understanding an unsupervised learning model can be a baby and her family cat. No one has explicitly taught the baby that this animal is a cat but when the baby’s relatives bring along a cat during their visit a few months later, the baby recognises that this animal is a cat based on its features (e.g. two pointy ears, four legs, whiskers, a long furry tail).
    </p>

    <p data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1500" data-aos-delay="150">
      Clustering is an important concept under unsupervised learning because it deals with finding patterns in a collection of uncategorised data. Clustering algorithms group input data based on similar features that they find, such as when Netflix recommends new shows based on what it has learnt your viewing preferences to be - from patterns in your viewing your history.
    </p>

